So there ya go, everyone. The one time I actually could have really used a public service that was dedicated to protecting the public, & instead I was stuck with having to call the police, who don't actually do that despite what all the copaganda TV shows would have you believe

He replied that he couldn't take a report because I didn't have a good enough description.Which was funny, because he hadn't asked me if I *had* a description. It was pretty clear he didn't want me to file a report, and I was reluctant to anyways, so that was that.

I pointed out that it seemed like knowing there was a potentially violent rando in a neighborhood near campus, where lots of students who were new to town had just moved in, might be considered to be in the public interest.
As soon as I described the homophobic nature of the incident, the cop literally said- I s2g it was like a bad screenplay- "well I don't see what we can do about that."

So I reluctantly called. I tried to figure out if there was any other way to do what I wanted- which was just "hey, make a note of this and tell people to be careful, and include this on the stats of discrimination"- w/o calling the PD, but couldn't find an alternative.

But I did get many people telling me to report it after the fact. That if *someone* knew, maybe they could keep it from happening to someone else. That I could file a report so that others knew the potential risk. That if I didn't call, no one would know it had happened.

So, a follow-up to the incident on Thursday.It didn't cross my mind to report it to the cops at the time. As violated and scared as I felt, I knew that calling 911 could lead to someone getting shot, and the relatively little harm done to me didn't justify that risk.

I appreciate the people who respond on twitter tend to have a beef and an agenda - twitter is *not* a representation of opinion worldwide (thankfully!). But - everyone has to do their part here in this next phase, basically until (hopefully) vaccination of high risk groups.

Furthermore, given the economic and livelihood impact of the sledgehammer of lockdowns - the only way many countries controlled the earlier infection wave - we should be totally happy to over-engineer - over-test - over-track - over-wear-masks etc.

Goverments at all levels - national to local, healthsystems and citizens have a lot more options, and are using them. There is no guarantee that they will collectively work but every chance that some combination will.

Therefore although there is still huge risks of uncontrolled, exponential infection - likely to cause the deaths of 0.5-1% of people and a severe disease for many more - we have more options to control and contain than we could have imagined back in March.

We have more options on the table in the near term - new tests emerge seemingly every week at the moment, sewage and a level of contact tracing which is at a new level. Vaccines and cures are happening far faster than expected.

In my view the reality is messier and more complex. The epidemic has no way ended - far from it - but we collectively understand SARS-CoV-2 and its disease, COVID19, far far better than the start of this year.

Some tweets are retweeted with comments that the infection is fully under control; that the level of severity of the epidemic was exaggerated; that we should stop worrying and ... blaming politicians for the outcomes.

Some of my tweets are retweeted with comments to imply it is hopeless; governments have lost their grip (if they ever had them); lockdowns should be reimposed quickly and blaming politicians for the outcomes.

Watching how my tweets on coronavirus get retweeted on or commented on I can see that in some cases the polarisation which twitter seems to enhance takes over. Reality is far far messier and complex than the polarised positions might make you think.

We demonstrated the use of STAAR-O in a WGS RV analysis of lipid traits using the TOPMed WGS data (12,316 discovery and 17,822 replication samples) using functional mask based gene-centric analysis and genetic region analysis using variant sets defined by 2-kb sliding windows(18/

In extensive simulations of various scenarios, STAAR-O achieves a significant power gain compared with conventional variant set tests weighted by MAF,  such as SKAT and burden, while maintaining accurate type I error rates for both quantitative and dichotomous phenotypes (17/)

STAAR-O is powerful when any of the incorporated variant functional annotations can pinpoint causal variants (and help boost power), and is robust to the directionality of effects and sparsity of causal variants in a variant set (16/)
STAAR-O is an omnibus test by combining p-values across different types of multiple annotation-weighted variant set tests (STAAR-burden, STAAR-SKAT, and STAAR-ACAT-V) using the ACAT method (15/)

Usually I end threads like this on a positive note, but we have a hurricane coming & tbh I‚Äôm worried for our coastal communities. This isn‚Äôt a Louisiana problem, it‚Äôs a national problem. We need to address climate change NOW to protect our Gulf Coast marshes & communities. https://t.co/95E2xZZfHB

But restoration is a temporary fix. Sea level rise & erosion threaten natural & created marshes, & a new study out of @Tulane says that we may have reached the tipping point for our Gulf Coast marshes. Basically, they can‚Äôt outpace sea level rise https://t.co/mD6sxzV0P1

Restoration efforts along the coast to stop this land loss & protect the remaining marsh as storm buffers are extensive. And they work! We are creating new land that IS helping to protect coastal communities. (Check out our American Scientist article for more details...) https://t.co/9IMybquGpf

And as we‚Äôre preparing for hurricane Laura, Louisiana is also dealing w the 15th anniversary of Hurricane Katrina, which disproportionately affected (& really, devastated) Black people in New Orleans. Many of these communities are still recovering today. https://t.co/b3C1pMZFaA

These environmental issues disproportionately affect poor & BIPOC communities. For example, Louisana‚Äôs Biloxi-Chitimaca-Choctaw tribe are being forced to relocate from their barrier island home due to rising seas, which cover the only road in in high tides https://t.co/bKD2bzV0hC

But, these coastal marshes have been carved up by the oil industry & no longer protect the coast like they used to. Now they‚Äôre also sinking with sea level rise. & w climate change, storms are getting worse in intensity, frequency, & duration, & so is inland flooding. (üì∏:CPRA) https://t.co/vu6vjYUaXY

This is bad for many reasons. Obviously, land loss = habitat loss. But also, these marshes act as buffers against storm surge. When coastal areas are flooded from say a giant hurricane, salt marshes absorb a lot of that water & minimize flooding in inland coastal communities. https://t.co/gaU8aCNLe7

Hmmm, seems like a good time to talk about coastal land loss in the Gulf of Mexico. Louisiana has 40% of the US‚Äôs wetlands & has lost >2k miles of coastal marsh since 1932 (that‚Äôs the size of DELAWARE). We still lose a football field of marsh evey 90 min. That‚Äôs...a lot of land. https://t.co/6saW0Eypj7

However, genetics is a very useful tool. Used well it often gives key insights into any biological question which involves living organisms that have DNA (and ideally have simple diploid genetics; plant+fungi researchers can extend to the madness of plant+fungi funky genetics!)

Genetics is not magic pixie dust. It is definitely *not* your destiny (the modern day, pseudo-astrological phrase "its in our DNA" should be banished!) and although it can provide hypothesis-free insight, often that insight is "this bit of biology is freakin' complex"

(though there are a host of gotchas if you do this wrong; ideally get a battlescarred statistical geneticist or genetic epidemiologist on your team and then earn your own scars if doing this the first time)

The ambiguous ACC terminology & small sampled studies limits what we understand & the translation of this into the clinical setting. Parents may receive or find inconsistent information which may heighten their distress. Care should be holistic & person-centred. https://t.co/8N8wBI6uFW

Despite knowing that prenatal diagnosis of a congenital anomaly can be distressing for parents, particularly when there is diagnostic/prognostic ambiguity- there were very limited recommendations for care for the parents, nothing explored their experience. We are onto that! https://t.co/5BMJvqCNjZ

Given the heterogeneity, ACC should be considered as an anatomical feature of an underlying condition rather than a specific entity (Raybaud, 2010). However, the underlying cause or accompanying conditions often remain unknown, especially in the prenatal period. https://t.co/QImB0bY1a5

There was a spectrum of neurodevelopmental outcomes for both people with isolated or non-isolated ACC. The studies were often limited by small samples, age of participants, mode of assessment, variables included & of course, the ambiguous ACC terminology & different inclusions. https://t.co/HjzoNWg8Jv

The prenatal diagnosis of ACC is increasing as tech & knowledge advances. ACC was diagnosed between weeks 17 ‚Äì 38. With a high amount of ‚Äòincidental‚Äô later gestation findings, the reported prevalence of ACC is likely to be an underestimate. https://t.co/Uoncu5mguQ

An example of what this means on the ground: the very common increasing dilation of the ventricles over the gestation (not assoc. w/ diff outcomes) may be interpreted as a secondary feature of ACC, or an extra finding - which will influence the prognosis offered to parents. https://t.co/Flua479gfi

Those other common neuro diff.: enlarged lat. ventricles, raised third vent, & changes to other commissures, cavum septum pellucidum, hippocampus and cingulate gyrus, often included, sometimes excluded from an isolated definition. Same with delayed sulcation, cysts & genetic v. https://t.co/M4YNBYifzX

Whether the ACC was isolated (the only/ main anom) or present with other anomalies was reported as the sig. factor for prognostic counselling. However, we found the very definition of isolated varied. Some researchers included other common neuro findings, others excluded these. https://t.co/JvDmkVkXRr

Agenesis of the #corpuscallosum (ACC) is a neurological #anomaly where the corpus callosum develops atypically during pregnancy. Many terms are used to describe ACC, some describe particular appearances of the corpus callosum, but the terms are inconsistent & overlap. https://t.co/yqqUuKXLYq

Hoping every #bioinformatician finds something that brings you happiness, keeps you going in upsetting moments, and makes you stronger :)To me, diving in the data mountain data sea definitely #sparksjoy!#AcademicTwitter #AcademicChatter #phdchat

lastly - which #roles of #bioinformatician do we want to avoid? isolated environment, lack of team support, receiving end of "can you fix my files/code/figures", website maintainer, free labor, help desk, or any other things that make us feel underappreciated. 8/n

Ask about your PI's expectation, are they looking for someone to lead independent projects or to support other people's projects? Some might be interested in both, therefore balancing #expectations is important - you'd be pretty much doing two persons' job. 7/n

one's boss' #expectation - this one is hard to manage. Open discussion at the beginning of hiring helps a lot. Hiring is a two-way street, we align each other's goals and decide if it works. If you want 1st author papers, say it. If you want growth in diverse skills, say it. 6/n

postdoc or staff scientists? Both roles can be successful in #acedamia or #industry, it really depends on what you want. Most important thing is to build skills towards your next career stage. Time is precious! Make sure you have something new to add to CV every six months. 5/n

one's own #expectation - 3 years from now, where do you see yourself will be? build skills towards that goal. If goal is #academia, 1st/last author #paper is key. if goal is #industry, #realworld experience is key, esp broad knowledge + sharp expertise in specific fields. 4/n

#environment - academia/industry, small/big lab, dry/wet lab. I highly recommend positions in a lab with #hybrid #expertise: wet+dry, clinical+dry, translational+dry, to grow #computational skills. Co-mentoring by two labs w each specializing in one are also great options. 3/n
We see a lot of discussion around the #role of #bioinformaticians in a project. Three factors in this equation: #environment, one's own #expectation, one's boss' expectation. 2/n

This regular alternation of Rt values above and below Rt=1 over the year is what causes the typical seasonal patterns we see for common colds and seasonal flu (e.g. pic below), and are observed in both hemispheres. (5/5)Source: https://t.co/2FhSJyfcdz https://t.co/nhaWasKVZO

The reproductive number of an epidemic (Rt) can be >1 irrespective of the season in the early on in an epidemic. Once a proportion of the host population has been immunised, (decreasing Rt), epidemic seasonality kicks in: in winter (and spring) Rt>1, and in summer Rt<1. (4/5)

The fact that a virus is seasonal does not mean that it cannot spread at any time of year when conditions are otherwise suitable. In the presence of a large reservoir of susceptible conditions, #SARSCoV2 can cause epidemics irrespective of climatic conditions. (3/5)

#SARSCoV2 is primarily transmitted through droplets in the air and these survive for longest in in cold, dry air, and possibly in the presence of low UV (sunlight). Though the virus can transmit in any climatic condition and through other means, but just less well. (2/5)

Contrary to recent claims, #SARSCoV2 is expected to be seasonal, as are essentially all >200 respiratory viruses in circulation, including the four 'common cold' coronaviruses (see below). (1/5)Source: https://t.co/RNk6V9CwEz https://t.co/fM4bQx1nKO

Some background:Our modeling study from February:https://t.co/uWj3IRxKkoA review of seasonal effects on respiratory viruses:https://t.co/8op3DLBmAT

We understand much better now what settings account for most transmission, so we can hopefully contain #SARSCoV2 without drastic restrictions --- but it probably won't be as easy as in summer. We need to act early and should head into winter with as few cases as possible.8/8

This is consistent with the pattern of the 2009 H1N1 pandemic (given it started 4 months later).To me, this suggests controlling #SARSCoV2 in the Northern Hemisphere will become a lot harder over the next six months and things might spiral out of control quickly.7/8

So far:  - Europe and Northern US saw big #SARSCoV2 winter/spring outbreaks. Social distancing (and maybe spring) helped contain them followed by fairly quiet summer - Southern US had a broad peak in summer - South America has large outbreaks in their winter.6/8 https://t.co/g8zSWNxnb4

The 2009 H1N1 pandemic had an overall lower R0 and thus seasonal forcing should be more impactful. It also spread rapidly among children, so school holidays likely had a big effect. But even if seasonal effects for #SARSCoV2 are less pronounced, I am still concerned.5/8

The UK saw a pattern similar to Northern US; the rest of Europe didn't see much H1N1 until fall -- probably driven by colder weather and the end of summer holidays. Germany saw a transition from middle-aged adults to children over the year (hard to see in the graph).4/8 https://t.co/STr6cPofrN

H1N1pdm arrived in many places in spring/early summer, earlier than #SARSCoV2 that started spreading in Dec from central China. With H1N1 in 2009, the North of the US saw distinct spring/summer and fall/winter waves, while the South saw one long peak.3/8 https://t.co/jbtwLhxBem

The 2009 H1N1 influenza pandemic might offer some clues. H1N1pdm is much less deadly, but much like #SARSCoV2 it - is an enveloped respiratory virus that spreads via droplets - in 2009 hit a mostly susceptible population(there are important differences too, see below)2/8 https://t.co/gyNnnC7yZn

What happens to #COVID19 when winter returns to the Northern Hemisphere is still uncertain, but here are some things we know: - people will spend more time indoors - indoor air will be drier and less ventilated - endemic CoVs have pronounced seasonality.1/8 https://t.co/UMMW4AmqSB

We found that when conditions are unfavourable, dengue virus spread cryptically, almost lying in wait, to finally resurge, when more susceptible hosts are available.Good reason to keep epidemiological surveillance: to detect viruses before they cause large epidemics.üí•ü¶†üëÄ

#Herdimmunity: when the number of susceptible individuals in a population is low, viruses may yet be able to replicate and transmit, but they do so at very low rates.That's what probably happened in Brazil: Zika hit hard, and left behind some level of protection against dengue.

In our study we provide further evidence of an interesting phenomenon: immunity from a previous infection by Zika virus may provide cross-protection against future dengue virus infections. This may explain the decline in dengue cases in the Americas ‚õîÔ∏èü¶†https://t.co/dJRnS1M6hH

Dengue declined in Brazil, and in most countries in the Americas. #Chikungunya cases also declined, but gradually, without resurgence in 2019. Infectious diseases are transmitted in a population of susceptible hosts following a rate called Force of Infection (FOI).@RJOidtman, @guido_camargo and @TAlexPerkins estimated dengue FOI for each region in Brazil, and found viral transmission was indeed quite low in 2017-2018. https://t.co/7iidNJYQtX

I just wanted to make it clear my approval of HEPA filters and sterilization in one case isn't necessarily approval for it in all cases. It could work in schools. I don't know. But I do know there's compelling evidence it works in planes. Thank you. Have a great Sunday.

There's a lot of combination prevention built into airplane cabins that gives the air purification process a leg-up. Please don't extrapolate evidence for efficacy in large buildings from airplane cabins. (3/4)

As I've previously said, mask compliance on planes is >99%, with little talking and movement in a small cabin that's easy to recirculate, i.e., the opposite of a school, which is large, low mask compliance, lots of talking, and a lot of movement and interactions (2/3)

[Short thread] When I say HEPA filters, along with UV and Ozone sterilization, are probably effective in airplanes, I'm ONLY talking about airplane cabins, where the entire cabin is recirculated every 2 to 3 mins. I'm not saying it applies to large buildings, e.g., schools

We estimate rates like dNS, where NS=nonsynonymous (N) in gene 1 but synonymous (S) in gene 2 (Fig 1B). OLGenie is our software for finding OLGs by detecting purifying selection (constraint) in one reading frame (gene 2) while controlling for another (gene 1). To do this, the Wei-Zhang method, tailored for OLGs, is modified to estimate dN/dS quickly. [3/7] https://t.co/He0eb0NBtq

Briefly, overlapping genes (OLGs) occur when a single stretch of nucleotides (ACGT...) encodes two distinct proteins in different reading frames. Kanagawa also has an alarmingly high positive rate. I think on weekends they prioritise cases with severe symptoms which explains some of this. Tokyo reports these as 7 day averages with a delay, I had to compute daily rates myself. I think we can see why they make it difficult. https://t.co/2FbcjjqUz6

For full disclosure, I was only able to find testing data for the past month. Kanagawa also has weekly seasonality in testing. EpiNow2 forecasts for both are both adjusted for this and positivity rate. I see many media outlets ignoring this and reporting emotional rollercoasters. https://t.co/8LEpBVxZCz

So can we believe this plateau? Is it safe to travel (there's a Japanese holiday next week). Let's look at Kanagawa where the 2nd largest city (Yokohama) is with millions of commuters to Tokyo a day. Trend is similar as expected but they continue to report record cases this week. https://t.co/033VUhlzo5

Testing labs in Tokyo have reduced capacity over the weekends so we see less cases reported a few days later. We can see the 4-day weekend at the end of July here and reduced testing this week. They announced new labs opening so maybe this is temporary? Positive rate is rising. https://t.co/OmKm9CuYUj

Are they testing enough? This has been a contentious issue in Japan for the entire pandemic frankly. Government claimed contact tracing was effective, no need for wider testing, and has failed to adapt. Several testing labs in Tokyo reached capacity last week delaying reporting. https://t.co/6i4zTSvZjc

The reported cases in Tokyo appear to have plateaued this week. Tokyo governor has suggested further restrictions but the national government does not seemed concerned (and have even incentivised travel for economic benefits). Should they be? Community transmissions are rising. https://t.co/ctcU0CmZry

This project is near and dear to my heart.  My first paper was on M. nervosa from when I was in high school. The reference specimen comes from my home town of Florence/Muscle Shoals. They are a hotbed of Unionid diversity.

So here is a species with genetic diversity as high as a fruit fly, but it is long lived.  Reproductive maturity is around 8 years of age. The longest lived in the literature is 43 yrs old, but there are claims of 57 years old.

M. nervosa is one species of Unionidae that has remained more robust in the face of modern threats to waterways, though numbers still may be diminishing.  In one reservoir there are estimates of millions of individuals. Genetic diversity is high, with theta=0.0077.

2017 piece by Scott Adams. Turns out he was right on multiple counts in his story arc: "second Hitler", "incompetent", "chaos", "we don't like it". But wrong on "effective". Also wrong on the arc playing sequentially: all of it is happening, all the time.  https://t.co/CDUxLeXfK5

We want to examine how genomes change as population sizes drop and species experience strong selective pressures.  With increased drift and strong selection do duplications, deletions, rearrangements and TEs play a larger role in genetic change?
Situation/surveillance are pointless if you don't have interventions, and the intervention could be bring high capacity testing solutions to a broad location for fine grained case identification.

It is not perfect; there is a host of issues on extraction and points of sampling; the sewage network does not reach and/or cannot be easily sampled anywhere near the whole population, though the most at risk broad area (urban) are likely to be biased towards ease of sampling

Here sewage needs to be considered as part of a surveillance / situational awareness scheme (along with cases across a country). The passive nature of sewage (people really don't have to change their habits at all) and large scale pooling means this is just excellent

The other big card to play is early, passive detection via Sewage. There is increasing evidence worldwide that the viral RNA is detectable in Sewage (thankfully it looks mainly deactivated by stomach acid presumably!). Sewage is a passive, at scale, pooling scheme
Finally we can think about pooling - 5 way or 10 way pooling which automatically increases capacity but then one needs to agonise about sensitivity follow up protocols.
We can go further. research evidence is that infectious people often shed into saliva; this can again simplify issues.

One positive is that many of these new testing schemes (including LamPORE from nanopore to be clear) offer far higher portability - in trucks. One can think more about bringing high capacity to a location and people management.

An important point about testing is even today the problem is not testing *capacity* it is testing *logistics/operations*. With the new technologies coming on-stream it is the logistics/operations side that needs as much effort as the technical capacity side.
How to do this? We need to test deeper, and do our upmost to test moderate to high risk individuals.

So, we need to push to the next level of reducing transmission by isolation. As a backstop we have to still have on the table large "lockdown" like measures. These though are massively disruptive and we should aim to avoid them if at all possible.
Secondly in the northern hemisphere it will be harder to easily be outside. We know high transmission risk is indoor places with poor ventilation; shouting and singing are not good.
The autumn involves changes in contact patterns. Firstly schools, in particular older students and universities would naturally come back and this implies far more contacts inside these groups.

Despite though this progress on treatments and vaccines - and we need to do this all as fast as can be done safely - we are looking at least navigating autumn, probably winter without a massive change to the profile of the disease on these two fronts.
Vaccines do not have to have perfect to be useful; reducing transmission by 50% would be great; reducing severity of disease by 50% would be great; anything higher or combinations of these - wow!

Vaccine progress has also been remarkable; there are over 100 candidate vaccines; a far smaller number have got to Phase 3 trials (I am one such person on a Phase 2/3 trial!). Noone would have predicted this progress in march.
Far further from my expertise are the smaller improvements in clinical care pathways (airflow improvements, anti-coagulants, proning etc). These too need to happen and be shared worldwide.

(I know this is hard to do logistically, and like many things in this pandemic it is all to easy to say on twitter or on a zoom call "do this" - far hard to execute and operationalise. All credit to all the clinical trialists who are doing this right now)

We need *more* straightforward, large, randomised clinical trials around COVID treatments. When you see the clear cut results from well powered trials you realise how much wasted energy we put into small scale trials or just no trials at all.

But one can be more flexible here; at the Nanopore adaptor stage one can use a second level of barcodes - their kits have 8-way, allowing 768 final parallel ("multiplexed") samples.

Once swabs are RNA extracted, the LAMP reaction happens (from 1 to ... 96) and then at this point one can just mix the resulting reactions, add the nanopore adaptors (which enable the DNA to be sequenced) and put on nanopore - up to 96 samples, <90mins

So - full circle back to LamPORE. Nanopore designed LAMP primers to the SARS-CoV-2 genome with a 96-way barcode. They actually have 4 sets of primers per sample reaction ('well' in molecular biology speak); 3 on the virus across different genes and one human RNA (beta actin)

How fast? Once DNA is introduced to the pore it will start reporting sequence within 15 minutes. The standard set up (called a "flow cell") has around 500 active pores (there is a trick about getting one pore per sensor which means this varies a bit).

And you can obviously put many of the "chip stations" side by side, which is their printer sized box. There is also a big daddy machine (a sort of small photocopier sized thing) which is too big for this.

How small? The actual pores and chips are mini-mini (smaller than many coins). They have made mobile phone compatible devices. But, in fact, to do everything in a sensible package (in particular the computing) their best device looks like a thick DVD player with door.

This is all super-fiddly and complex, and over a while @nanopore have gotten all of it to work. There are some pros and cons vs other ways of determining DNA sequence but the two important ones here is that (a) devices are small and (b) they are super fast.

You can measure this differential passage of water ions relative to time with a sensitive chip and if the single nanopore is placed over one chip sensor - and some v. smart algorithms to sort out the signal - you can work out the DNA sequence that came through the pore.

That's the LAMP bit; now onto the Nanopore bit. Nanopore uses a tiny protein pore (a nanopore) in a lipid bilayer (like a soap bubble) and when DNA passess through the pore in a controlled manner the amount of water ions that can pass by the DNA is specific to the DNA sequence

(this is sometimes called multiplexing, though multiplexing is also used for other quite different techniques; DNA barcoding is more specific and ends up being limited only by primer design and robotics)

The unique barcode means after the molecular biology processes you can simply mix the resulting reactions. If you use DNA sequencing as a readout then the barcode assigns each molecule to a unique starting reaction. So in this case you can do 96 reactions in parallel

An brief explainer on "DNA barcodes". DNA barcodes is shorthand for designing schemes where the DNA you introduce has a segment that changes under your own design plus the standard business end. In this case, there are 96 slightly different primer sets, each with a unique barcode
(LAMP amplification diagrams completely bamboozle me, and I hear that the barcode insertion makes it even more complex)

The downside of the explosive amplification, which has the potential for cross-contamination is controlled somewhat by the format but most of all that @nanopore cleverly designed their first layer of barcodes *into* the LAMP primer design. This is fiddly.
This means if you precisely measure the DNA primer amounts in differnet tubes you get the same molarity of resulting amplified products. This is super useful.

..or require reasoning about the effects of strategic intervention.  Yet, rarely are the tools of causal inference applied in sports.

One of the main takeaways that we highlight in the discussion is the need for more causal thinking in sports.  So many of the key questions basketball involve a comparison between an observed outcome and a counterfactual outcome (e.g. wins above replacement)...

There are also algorithms using roots of unity. A char in the pattern and the same char in the text must be roots of unity that become 1 when multiplied. Two different characters' product's real component would be less than 1. A match must have real component sum = pattern length
The reason why the difference is squared is because we don't want the differences to cancel out when we add them. For indexes that mismatch, there would be a nonzero value after the convolution.

The cool thing is that the algorithm for checking exact matches is surprisingly simple: c[i] = \sum_j (t[i + j] - p[j])^2 = \sum_j t[i + j]^2 - t[i + j]p[j] + p[j]^2. All indexes i where t[i] = 0 are matches. In total this takes O(N log N) time with FFT convolution. https://t.co/voyAeWVPSQ
